event: response.output_item.done
data: {"type":"response.output_item.done","sequence_number":600,"output_index":27,"item":{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1peyfv2v3dpt6yem7510","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 5, \"id\": 7}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL: https://www.reuters.com/world/us/crisis-point-2026-04-09/\nL2: Iran war tests Trump’s most enduring political gifts \\| Reuters\nL3: \nL4: 【0†Exclusive news, data and analytics for financial market professionalsLearn\nL5: more aboutRefinitiv】\nL6: \nL7: People walk next to a mural depicting the late leader of the Islamic Revolution\nL8: Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and the late Supreme Leader of Iran Ayatollah Ali\nL9: Khamenei, after U.S. President... 【1†Purchase Licensing Rights, opens new\nL10: tab†www.reutersconnect.com】Read more\nL11: \nL12: April 9 - The Iran war is ending. Or so the White House says. The last-minute\nL13: ceasefire this week in a conflict that has convulsed capitals from Washington to\nL14: Brussels to Tehran has left several key issues up in the air. What does it mean\nL15: politically? And will it last?\nL16: \nL17: Last week, President Donald Trump stepped inside a Washington theater, the lights\nL18: dimmed and Broadway performers crooned about how to wow an audience.\nL19: \nL20: “Razzle dazzle 'em, and they'll beg you for more,” goes one of the songs,\nL21: from “Chicago.” “Give 'em an ‌act with lots of flash in it, and the\nL22: reaction will be passionate.”\nL23: \nL24: It’s not clear what Trump may have taken from the Jazz Age musical. But\nL25: Trump’s own mastery of spectacle has been key to his decades in public life.\nL26: \nL27: It’s a political gift being tested by a war with Iran that has 【2†divided\nL28: the nation】, his political base and the 【3†NATO alliance】.\nL29: \nL30: Trump again demonstrated his ability to dominate the public conversation this\nL31: week. His press conference on Monday refocused attention on the war to 【4†a\nL32: daring rescue】of an airman stranded deep inside enemy territory.\nL33: \nL34: His 【5†profanity-laced tirade】on 【6†Easter】and his later\nL35: 【7†eleventh-hour decision】to call off what he described as a\nL36: civilization-ending attack on Iran transfixed and alarmed people around the\nL37: globe. A Trump administration official told my colleague that ⁠Trump’s most\nL38: charged rhetoric 【8†came from the president himself】as he sought to create\nL39: leverage through unpredictability.\nL40: \nL41: The president’s ability to control the facts on the ground has been far more\nL42: tenuous than his ability to shape the narrative. Despite achieving tactical\nL43: military wins in Iran, the United States could still fall short of his declared\nL44: goals.\nL45: \nL46: In the two days since Trump declared the ceasefire, no one has released a\nL47: comprehensive document detailing the agreement’s terms. Neither side agrees on\nL48: what the deal is precisely. Iran has not publicly conceded Washington’s key\nL49: demands and the Strait of Hormuz is not fully open to traffic. Tehran has not\nL50: publicly agreed to halt its nuclear program nor to stop arming groups abroad.\nL51: \nL52: At home, Americans remain skeptical of a war that has dragged into a sixth week\nL53: and further eroded Trump’s job approval rating. 【9†U.S. gas prices】are\nL54: set to remain elevated through the crucial summertime driving season.\nL55: \nL56: The unfinished work in the Middle East has exposed the limits – and risks - of\nL57: 【10†Trump’s strategy】of making apocalyptic threats and backing down.\nL58: Critics mocked what they saw as another example of “TACO,” or “Trump always\nL59: chickens out,” and even some of Trump's fellow Republicans openly expressed\nL60: concern about the president’s chilling rhetoric.\nL61: \nL62: There’s no ‌doubt that ⁠Trump’s showmanship can control attention. But as\nL63: the gap between his rhetoric and an unstable Middle East expands, he may leave\nL64: his audience asking what’s real.\nL65: \nL66: ## TOP US POLITICS HEADLINES\nL67: \nL68: 【9†US pump prices to stay elevated despite US-Iran ceasefire deal, market\nL69: observers say】\nL70: \nL71: 【10†Trump's abrupt Iran reversal exposes limits of his leverage】\nL72: \nL73: 【11†Evangelicals amplify Trump's religious framing of Iran war】\nL74: \nL75: 【12†Draw it yourself: Checking Trump’s tariff claims a year later】\nL76: \nL77: 【4†Trump seizes on rescue of downed airman to recast unpopular Iran war】\nL78: \nL79: ## CHART OF THE WEEK\nL80: \nL81: Stacked bar chart showing a majority of Americans worry about the Iran war's\nL82: impact on their personal finances and more generally about the financial costs of\nL83: military action in Iran.\nL84: \nL85: ## THE VIEW FROM BEIRUT\nL86: \nL87: What ceasefire? That’s a question on the minds of residents of Lebanon. The\nL88: two-week truce in the Iran war has provided no end to an 【13†Israeli bombing\nL89: campaign there】. Both Iran ⁠and ceasefire mediator Pakistan understood that\nL90: the ceasefire agreement included Lebanon, where Iran’s Hezbollah allies are\nL91: entrenched. The White House and Israel said that was not the case.\nL92: \nL93: If the ceasefire agreement unravels, Lebanon may be the reason. Israeli Prime\nL94: Minister Benjamin Netanyahu sees Iran and affiliated groups across the region as\nL95: in retreat but not fully defeated. By creating \"buffer zones\" in Gaza, Syria and\nL96: Lebanon, he hopes to push them back as far as ⁠possible. But it also means\nL97: 【14†a semi-permanent state of war】, Israeli military and defense officials\nL98: told my colleagues in Jerusalem. Washington may be dragged back into the Middle\nL99: East for years to come.\nL100: \nL101: ## WHAT TO WATCH FOR\nL102: \nL103: April 9: Rev. Al Sharpton's National Action Network hosts potential 2028\nL104: Democratic candidates\nL105: \nL106: April 11: US, Iran may meet for negotiations in Islamabad\nL107: \nL108: April 13: Trump meets with Dutch King Willem-Alexander\nL109: \nL110: April 16: Election to fill seat ⁠vacated by New Jersey Governor Mikie Sherrill\nL111: (NJ-11)\nL112: \nL113: April 17: Trump speaks at Turning Point USA event in Phoenix\nL114: \nL115: ## THE WHO, WHAT AND WHEN\nL116: \nL117: 【15†Highs and lows from the US jobs report】\nL118: \nL119: 【16†Can the US and Iran bridge their differences in talks?】\nL120: \nL121: 【17†Trump’s mixed messages and Iran’s bombs kept the Kurds out of the\nL122: war】\nL123: \nL124: Reporting by Trevor Hunnicutt; Editing by Colleen Jenkins and Alistair Bell\nL125: \nL126: Our Standards: 【18†The Thomson Reuters Trust Principles., opens new\nL127: tab†www.thomsonreuters.com】\nL128: \nL129: Thomson Reuters\nL130: \nL131: Trevor Hunnicutt is White House Correspondent at Reuters News. He writes about\nL132: U.S. foreign and domestic policy and regularly travels with the President of the\nL133: United States. Prior to joining the White House team in 2021, he covered\nL134: presidential campaigns, economics, finance and investing for many years. He has\nL135: also served on the board of the White House Correspondents' Association.\nL136: Hunnicutt holds a bachelor's degree from Pomona College and a master's from the\nL137: London School of Economics.\nL138: \nL139: ## World\nL140: \nL141: ### Former Brazil spy chief freed in the US after ICE detention, Bolsonaro ally\nL142: says\nL143: \nL144: 【19†Americascategory】· April 15, 2026 · 10:59 PM UTC · ago\nL145: \nL146: Former Brazilian intelligence chief Alexandre Ramagem has ‌been freed in the\nL147: United States, said Paulo Figueiredo, an ally of former President Jair\nL148: ⁠Bolsonaro who lives in the U.S., on Wednesday.\nL149: \nL150: 【20†United Statescategory】【21†Mamdani, Hochul propose tax on New York\nL151: second homes worth more than $5 million】\nL152: \nL153: 【22†Businesscategory】【23†Ukraine official expects US-Ukrainian\nL154: investment fund to approve second project in summer】\nL155: \nL156: 【24†Worldcategory】【25†Mark Mobius, 'Indiana Jones of emerging markets,'\nL157: dies at 89】\nL158: \nL159: 【24†Worldcategory】【26†Scenes from Coachella】"}}

