ull,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag18g7fqps30e85sn681e9","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 1, \"id\": 8}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL: https://www.britannica.com/event/2026-Iran-war\nL2: 2026 Iran war \\| Explained, United States, Israel, Strait of Hormuz, Map, \u0026\nL3: Conflict \\| Britannica\nL4: \nL5: 【0†2026 Iran war†cdn.britannica.com】(more)\nL6: \nL7: # 2026 Iran war\nL8: \nL9: Middle Eastern history\nL10: \nL11: Ask Anything Homework Help\nL12: \nL13: Written and fact-checked by\nL14: \nL15: Britannica Editors\nL16: \nL17: Last updated\nL18: \nL19: Apr. 15, 2026 • 【1†History】\nL20: \nL21: Britannica AI\nL22: \nL23: Ask Anything\nL24: \nL25: Table of Contents\nL26: \nL27: Table of Contents Ask Anything\nL28: \nL29: Top Questions\nL30: \nL31: ### What is Operation Epic Fury?\nL32: \nL33: 【2†Operation Epic Fury】, which began on February 28, 2026, is the\nL34: 【3†U.S.】code name for its joint military operations with\nL35: 【4†Israel】against 【5†Iran】. The opening salvo took out the heart of\nL36: the Iranian regime, Supreme Leader 【6†Ali Khamenei】, and triggered a\nL37: torrent of hundreds of retaliatory missiles and thousands of drones from Iran\nL38: across the 【7†Middle East】. The attacks have left enormous damage,\nL39: thousands of people dead in Iran, 【8†Lebanon】, Israel, and the 【9†Gulf\nL40: Arab states】, and millions of people displaced in the region.\nL41: \nL42: ### What were the main reasons for tensions between the United States and Iran\nL43: before the 2026 conflict?\nL44: \nL45: Tensions between the 【3†United States】and 【5†Iran】stretch back to the\nL46: 【10†Islamic Revolution】in 1979 and the subsequent 【11†Iran hostage\nL47: crisis】, which set a tone of mutual hostility and deep distrust. The immediate\nL48: concerns leading up to the 【2†2026 Iran war】included Iran’s nuclear\nL49: program, its 【12†ballistic missiles】, its military reach in the\nL50: 【7†Middle East】region, and failed attempts to 【13†renegotiate a nuclear\nL51: deal】after the collapse of the 2015 【14†Joint Comprehensive Plan of\nL52: Action】(JCPOA) nuclear agreement.\nL53: \nL54: ### How did the United States and Israel begin their military operation against\nL55: Iran?\nL56: \nL57: On February 28, 2026, 【3†U.S.】and 【4†Israeli】forces launched nearly\nL58: 900 strikes in 12 hours targeting Iranian missiles, air defenses, military\nL59: infrastructure, and leadership. The initial wave of strikes killed Supreme Leader\nL60: 【6†Ali Khamenei】and dozens of other officials, but it also killed about 170\nL61: people when a missile struck a girls’ school adjacent to a naval base in Minab,\nL62: near 【15†Bandar Abbas】.\nL63: \nL64: ### What was Iran’s response to the strikes by the United States and Israel in\nL65: February 2026?\nL66: \nL67: In response to the attacks by the 【3†United States】and 【4†Israel】on\nL68: 【5†Iran】on February 28, 2026, Iran launched retaliatory\nL69: 【16†missile】and 【17†drone】strikes targeting U.S. embassies, military\nL70: installations, and oil infrastructure (including vessels in the 【18†Strait of\nL71: Hormuz】) throughout the 【7†Middle East】. Iran hoped its broad retaliation\nL72: would exact costs and pressure its adversaries into mediation.\nL73: \nL74: ### What was the global impact of the 2026 Iran war?\nL75: \nL76: The 2026 Iran war disrupted global travel and trade, halted flights in and out of\nL77: the 【7†Middle East】, and led to shipping reroutes to avoid the\nL78: 【18†Strait of Hormuz】and the 【19†Red Sea】.\nL79: \nL80: ## News •\nL81: \nL82: 【20†Pakistani army chief visits Tehran in bid to broker renewed talks between\nL83: US and Iran】• Apr. 16, 2026, 12:14 AM ET (AP) ...(Show more)\nL84: \nL85: 【21†Pakistani delegation meets in Tehran hoping for more US-Iran talks before\nL86: ceasefire ends】• Apr. 15, 2026, 7:38 PM ET (AP)\nL87: \nL88: 【22†Wall Street hits a record as S\u0026P 500 continues its 2-week rally on hopes\nL89: for an end to the Iran war】• Apr. 15, 2026, 5:19 PM ET (AP)\nL90: \nL91: 【23†Senate Republicans reject effort to halt Iran war, but some eye future\nL92: war powers votes】• Apr. 15, 2026, 4:41 PM ET (AP)\nL93: \nL94: 【24†WHO says vaccinations save millions in Africa, but US aid cuts and Iran\nL95: war threaten progress】• Apr. 15, 2026, 12:34 PM ET (AP)\nL96: \nL97: Show less\nL98: \nL99: 2026 Iran war, conflict centered on 【5†Iran】that was initiated by the\nL100: 【3†United States】and 【4†Israel】on February 28, 2026, and has upended\nL101: the 【25†dynamics†www.merriam-webster.com】of the 【7†Middle East】.\nL102: The opening salvo took out the heart of the Iranian regime, Supreme Leader\nL103: 【6†Ali Khamenei】, and triggered a torrent of hundreds of retaliatory\nL104: missiles and thousands of drones from Iran across the region. The conflict left\nL105: enormous damage, thousands of people dead in Iran and 【8†Lebanon】, dozens\nL106: dead in Israel and the 【9†Gulf Arab states】, and millions of people\nL107: displaced in the region, including more than one-sixth of the population in\nL108: Lebanon. The danger of crossfire and threats from Iran in particular led to\nL109: severe disruption of traffic through the 【18†Strait of Hormuz】, one of the\nL110: world’s most 【26†volatile oil】chokepoints, leading to fuel shortages in\nL111: parts of Asia and rippling effects across the global economy. After more than\nL112: five weeks of fighting, the United States and Iran agreed on April 7–8 to a\nL113: two-week ceasefire that included Israel.\nL114: \nL115: The 【27†confrontation】took place after years of rising tension over\nL116: Iran’s nuclear program, its 【12†ballistic missiles】, and its military\nL117: reach across the Middle East. Attempts to 【13†renegotiate a nuclear\nL118: deal】(after the collapse of the 【14†Joint Comprehensive Plan of\nL119: Action】\\[JCPOA\\]) in 2025 and 2026 were unsuccessful. Meanwhile, Iran’s\nL120: posture was in a weakened state after years of sanctions, recent\nL121: 【28†destabilizing protests】, damage inflicted during the 【29†12-day\nL122: War】with Israel in June 2025, and the diminished position of Iran’s allies\nL123: during the 【30†Israel-Hamas War】. Given Iran’s weakened position, the\nL124: United States and Israel calculated that they had greater opportunity to advance\nL125: their objectives through military means than by diplomatic means.\nL126: \nL127: ## Conflict\nL128: \nL129: 【31†U.S.-Israeli strikes on Tehran†cdn.britannica.com】Plume of smoke\nL130: rising from the Iranian capital, Tehran, from U.S.-Israeli strikes on March 3,\nL131: 2026.(more)\nL132: \nL133: Midmorning on February 28, U.S. and Israeli forces began conducting joint strikes\nL134: on Iran, numbering nearly 900 in just the first 12 hours of what the United\nL135: States dubbed Operation Epic Fury. The attacks targeted Iranian missiles and air\nL136: defenses, other military 【32†infrastructure†www.merriam-webster.com】, and\nL137: Iranian leadership. According to U.S. and Israeli officials, the timing of the\nL138: initial attack was tied in part to the ability to target 【6†Ali Khamenei】,\nL139: Iran’s 【33†supreme leader】, before he would go into hiding. Khamenei was\nL140: killed in the first wave of strikes on February 28, as were dozens of other top\nL141: Iranian officials. The attacks generated immediate controversy when it was\nL142: reported that a girls’ school in a town east of 【15†Bandar Abbas】was\nL143: struck, killing about 170 people. U.S. forces are believed to have conducted the\nL144: strikes, according to a preliminary investigation by the U.S. military, while\nL145: targeting 【34†adjacent†www.merriam-webster.com】buildings that belonged to\nL146: an 【35†Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps】(IRGC) naval base.\nL147: \nL148: 【36†Disrupting the regime†cdn.britannica.com】Israeli strikes destroyed\nL149: the building where Iran's Assembly of Experts was expected on March 3, 2026,\nL150: delaying Iran's ability to select a new supreme leader after Ali Khamenei was\nL151: killed.(more)\nL152: \nL153: Iran’s government was quick to prevent a vacuum in leadership, and its swift\nL154: movement to replace leaders killed in the conflict indicated both the stability\nL155: of the regime and the resolve of Iran’s hard-liners in the face of conflict.\nL156: 【37†Ali Larijani】, a broadly trusted senior official who had been serving\nL157: as the secretary of the Supreme National Security Council, was believed to have\nL158: been the 【38†de facto】leader of Iran in the immediate aftermath of\nL159: Khamenei’s death and following preparations to that effect before the\nL160: 【39†war】began. 【40†Mojtaba Khamenei】, who was considered more hawkish\nL161: and repressive than his father, was appointed supreme leader in early March\nL162: despite protests from U.S. Pres. 【41†Donald Trump】that he would consider\nL163: that appointment “unacceptable.” When Larijani was killed on March 17, he was\nL164: replaced by Mohammad Bagher Zolghadr, an appointment that reflected the\nL165: paramountcy of the IRGC over the political or clerical establishments in Iran’s\nL166: wartime decision-making.\nL167: \nL168: Meanwhile, retaliatory missile and 【42†drone】strikes by Iran embroiled the\nL169: region. They followed a familiar pattern of horizontal escalation,\nL170: 【43†according to the international security scholar Robert A.\nL171: Pape†www.foreignaffairs.com】writing in 【44†Foreign Affairs】. Iran’s\nL172: war strategy widened the arena of conflict, thereby extending the conflict beyond\nL173: mere military might and into the political and economic realms, with the aim of\nL174: withstanding bombardment until the conflict would become too costly for the\nL175: United States and Israel to be willing to sustain. Iranian strikes targeted U.S.\nL176: embassies and military installations in the 【45†United Arab Emirates】,\nL177: 【46†Saudi Arabia】, 【47†Qatar】, 【48†Kuwait】, 【49†Bahrain】,\nL178: 【50†Iraq】, 【51†Oman】, and 【52†Jordan】. 【53†NATO】forces\nL179: struck down Iranian drones and missiles near the Incirlik Air Base in\nL180: 【54†Turkey】(Türkiye).\nL181: \nL182: Explore Britannica Premium!\nL183: \nL184: Smart, reliable knowledge for professionals, students, and curious minds\nL185: everywhere.\nL186: \nL187: 【55†Strait of Hormuz†cdn.britannica.com】(more)\nL188: \nL189: Iranian attacks also targeted oil infrastructure in the region—including\nL190: vessels in the 【18†Strait of Hormuz】, through which 20 percent of the\nL191: world’s oil passes—as well as commercial 【56†hubs】in neighboring\nL192: countries that aid the U.S. military. By late March officials in the IRGC\nL193: suggested Iran may push its 【57†Houthi】allies in 【58†Yemen】to block\nL194: 【59†Bab el-Mandeb Strait】to disrupt shipping in the 【19†Red Sea】and\nL195: further strain global markets. It remained unclear whether the Houthi movement,\nL196: which in 2025 had reached a ceasefire with the United States in relation to its\nL197: attacks on Red Sea shipping, was willing to confront U.S. pressure directly, but\nL198: on March 28 it launched missiles and drones toward Israel and opened a new front\nL199: in the expanding regional conflict.\nL200: \nL201: The Strait of Hormuz increasingly became a focal point of the war in March,\nL202: particularly as other countries hesitated to enter the conflict in order to\nL203: enforce safe passage. On March 21 Trump threatened to target Iran’s civilian\nL204: energy infrastructure if Iran did not agree to allow ships to pass through the\nL205: Strait of Hormuz without interference. He then extended the threat to\nL206: 【60†Kharg Island】, the terminal for nearly all of Iran’s oil exports, and\nL207: to 【61†desalination】plants on March 30. Days later he set a deadline for\nL208: Iran of April 7 and took to 【62†social media】with a series of increasingly\nL209: 【63†vehement†www.merriam-webster.com】posts. On the morning of April 7 he\nL210: wrote in one such post that “a whole civilization will die tonight, never to be\nL211: brought back again.”\nL212: \nL213: On April 7–8 Trump announced on social media that he had agreed to a two-week\nL214: ceasefire brokered by Pakistan. Moments later, Iranian officials confirmed that\nL215: Khamenei had approved the ceasefire after a last-minute nudge by China.\nL216: \nL217: ## Conflict in Lebanon\nL218: \nL219: The conflict also saw the resumption of hostilities between Israel and Iran’s\nL220: close ally 【64†Hezbollah】in 【8†Lebanon】, which had been observing a\nL221: fragile ceasefire since 2024. Despite the ceasefire, which required the\nL222: disarmament of Hezbollah and the 【65†withdrawal】of the 【66†Israel\nL223: Defense Forces】(IDF) from southern Lebanon, Hezbollah had been seeking to\nL224: restore its military capabilities and the IDF had continued to strike targets in\nL225: southern Lebanon almost daily. After the opening wave of attacks on Iran on\nL226: February 28, the IDF conducted air strikes on Hezbollah’s infrastructure and\nL227: warned the militant group against getting involved in the conflict with Iran. On\nL228: March 2, Hezbollah launched missiles and drones into Israel, prompting an\nL229: escalation in Israeli air strikes that reached north to southern\nL230: 【67†Beirut】. A drone believed to have been launched by Hezbollah also\nL231: struck a base in 【68†Cyprus】used by the British 【69†Royal Air Force】.\nL232: In the following days Israel issued sweeping evacuation orders across southern\nL233: Lebanon, displacing more than 1,000,000 people by late March, as Israel prepared\nL234: for a ground invasion.\nL235: \nL236: A limited invasion began on March 17 amid reports that a broader ground offensive\nL237: was likely. On March 24 Israeli minister of defense Israel Katz announced plans\nL238: for the IDF to occupy southern Lebanon up to the 【70†Litani River】, a swath\nL239: of territory that the IDF had previously occupied in 1982 during the\nL240: 【71†Lebanese Civil War】(1975–90) until Israeli forces withdrew in 2000.\nL241: \nL242: ## Reactions and impact\nL243: \nL244: ## Initial reactions\nL245: \nL246: The outbreak of conflict between three widely impactful countries led to a burst\nL247: of reactions, ranging from anticipation to condemnation to confrontation. Many\nL248: observers, including Iranians in the\nL249: 【72†diaspora†www.merriam-webster.com】, hoped for the collapse of the\nL250: oppressive Islamic Republic of Iran and a decisive end to its nuclear program and\nL251: military reach. Within Iran, some Iranians celebrated Khamenei’s death while\nL252: proponents of the regime mourned; security forces stepped up their presence in\nL253: 【73†Tehran】to crack down on celebrations and public dissent.\nL254: 【51†Oman】, which attempted to mediate negotiations between the United\nL255: States and Iran, expressed disappointment that the “active and serious\nL256: negotiations” were abandoned. 【74†Russia】, Iran’s ally, condemned the\nL257: U.S. and Israeli strikes as destabilizing but showed little interest in\nL258: intervening on Iran’s behalf. Some countries questioned the legal basis of the\nL259: initial U.S. and Israeli attack, while others 【75†urged】Iran to show\nL260: restraint in its response and condemned its attacks on its neighbors.\nL261: 【76†Spain】, a NATO member that had already squabbled with U.S. demands\nL262: during the second Trump administration, refused to allow the United States to use\nL263: its air bases, leading Trump to threaten to cut trade with the country.\nL264: \nL265: ## Global economic impact and the Strait of Hormuz\nL266: \nL267: The war had immediate impacts on global travel and trade. Flights in and out of\nL268: the Middle East came to a near-complete stop, stranding residents, expatriates,\nL269: and tourists alike, even as Iran struck the region’s most crowded cities and\nL270: luxury hotels. When Dubai International Airport, one of the world’s busiest,\nL271: was damaged by 【17†drone】strikes during the second day of the conflict, it\nL272: temporarily halted all flights and reopened in only a limited\nL273: 【77†capacity】a few days later.\nL274: \nL275: 【78†Impact on tourism and commerce†cdn.britannica.com】A yacht sailing\nL276: away from Dubai's Jebel Ali port as smoke billows from an Iranian strike on March\nL277: 1, 2026.(more)\nL278: \nL279: Shipping lines rerouted to avoid the 【18†Strait of Hormuz】—even before\nL280: Iran threatened to fire on ships passing through the strait—as well as the\nL281: 【19†Red Sea】, where the Iran-allied 【57†Houthi movement】had\nL282: previously attacked ships in response to the 【30†Israel-Hamas War】.\nL283: Although commercial traffic through the Strait of Hormuz dropped more than 90\nL284: percent after the outbreak of conflict, Iran’s attacks on traffic in March\nL285: caused a further decline. It then selectively approved the transit of some ships,\nL286: including some Iranian ships, some ships belonging to countries that negotiated\nL287: safe passage with Iran, and some ships that were willing to pay Iran a hefty\nL288: toll. The disruption of oil flows out of the 【79†Persian Gulf】quickly led\nL289: to fuel shortages and rationing in parts of 【80†Asia】east of the gulf,\nL290: which rely heavily on oil supplied through the Strait of Hormuz, as well as a\nL291: sharp increase in price in the global oil market. Prices surged from about $70\nL292: per barrel just before the war to an average of $103 per barrel in March. While\nL293: the increase was disruptive for much of the global economy, the surge led to a\nL294: 【81†windfall】for Iran, which in March saw an average boost in oil revenue\nL295: of nearly $25 million per day, and Russia, which saw an average increase of about\nL296: $150 million per day in the same period.\nL297: \nL298: ## Background\nL299: \nL300: 【82†1953 coup in Iran: Protests in Tehran†cdn.britannica.com】Iranian\nL301: rioters armed with staves protesting against the coup, backed by the CIA and\nL302: British intelligence, that overthrew the democratically elected Prime Minister\nL303: Mohammad Mosaddegh, August 1953, Tehran.(more)\nL304: \nL305: Relations between 【5†Iran】and the 【3†United States】have long been\nL306: tense. The United States and Israel were both close allies with Iran’s\nL307: government until the 1979 【10†Islamic Revolution】. But U.S. intervention in\nL308: Iranian affairs became a sore spot for Iranians, particularly after U.S.\nL309: involvement in the 【83†1953 coup d’état】propped up the unpopular\nL310: 【84†Pahlavi】monarchy. When the revolution took place, the revolutionaries\nL311: blamed the United States and Israel for the region’s greatest grievances. The\nL312: 【11†Iran hostage crisis】only served to heighten tensions.\nL313: \nL314: 【85†The Axis of Resistance†cdn.britannica.com】(more)\nL315: \nL316: Matters escalated significantly in the early 2000s when Iran was revealed to have\nL317: a suspiciously secret nuclear program and, as U.S.-led forces toppled the regime\nL318: of 【86†Saddam Hussein】in 【50†Iraq】that fiercely opposed Iranian\nL319: expansion, Iran expanded its reach across the region (see 【87†Axis of\nL320: Resistance】). Efforts to contain Iran diplomatically proved fragile, especially\nL321: after 2018, when the United States withdrew from the 2015 【14†JCPOA】.\nL322: \nL323: 【88†Tehran: first responders on June 13,\nL324: 2025†cdn.britannica.com】Following a series of strikes across Iran on June 13,\nL325: 2025, first responders gather outside a damaged building in Tehran.(more)\nL326: \nL327: In 2024, during the 【30†Israel-Hamas War】, Israel significantly diminished\nL328: Iran’s reach in the 【7†Middle East】, tipping the regional 【89†balance\nL329: of power】in 【4†Israel】’s favor. Most notably, Israel decapitated\nL330: Iran’s close ally 【64†Hezbollah】in 【8†Lebanon】in\nL331: September–November, which in turn\nL332: 【90†facilitated†www.merriam-webster.com】【91†Ahmed al-Sharaa】’s\nL333: toppling of pro-Iran 【92†Syrian】Pres. 【93†Bashar al-Assad】in\nL334: December. Meanwhile, direct exchange of fire between Israel and Iran in April and\nL335: in October exposed vulnerabilities in Iran’s air defenses and damaged some of\nL336: Iran’s key military assets.\nL337: \nL338: The 【29†12-Day War】in June 2025 was the first test of open conflict between\nL339: the two 【7†Middle East】powers. Israel quickly debilitated Iran’s air\nL340: defenses and caused significant damage to Iran’s military and nuclear\nL341: infrastructure. The conflict ended after the United States struck underground\nL342: nuclear facilities in Fordow, Natanz, and 【94†Isfahan】using U.S. GBU-57 A/B\nL343: “bunker buster” bombs, an operation that Trump said was intended to be a\nL344: limited, one-off mission. A preliminary, low-confidence report from the U.S.\nL345: 【95†Defense Intelligence Agency】—in what the Trump administration\nL346: characterized as a “political” leak to the press—assessed that Iran had\nL347: moved much of its stockpile of enriched 【96†uranium】before the U.S. strikes\nL348: took place and that the strikes, which did not collapse the underground\nL349: facilities according to the report, set back Iran’s ability to produce nuclear\nL350: weapons by only a matter of months. The following day John Ratcliffe, the\nL351: director of the 【97†CIA】, said new information indicated severe damage to\nL352: the nuclear facilities that would take years for Iran to rebuild.\nL353: \nL354: Quick Facts\nL355: \nL356: In the aftermath of the 12-Day War, Iran’s 【98†currency】entered a free\nL357: fall, 【99†exacerbated†www.merriam-webster.com】by the imposition in\nL358: September of new international sanctions. The economic spiral led to the outbreak\nL359: of 【28†protests】on December 28, 2025, which, at the encouragement of the\nL360: United States, spread in January 2026 across Iran (see 【28†2026 Iranian\nL361: protests】). Trump threatened U.S. intervention if Iranian security forces\nL362: killed protesters. Nevertheless, on January 8 security forces unleashed a brutal\nL363: crackdown, killing at least 30,000 people, according to officials in Iran’s\nL364: Ministry of Health. In the weeks that followed, the United States undertook its\nL365: largest military buildup in the Middle East since its 【100†2003 invasion of\nL366: Iraq】.\nL367: \nL368: 1 of 3\nL369: \nL370: 【101†The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica】"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag191kfqvryp52s6f9v4p6","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"search","arguments":"{\"query\": \"Iran oorlog 2026 laatste nieuws\", \"topn\": 10, \"source\": \"news\"}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1aeyfr4atbcz42pmarcf","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"search","arguments":"{\"query\": \"Iran oorlog 2026 laatste nieuws\", \"topn\": 10, \"source\": \"news\"}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL: https://exa.ai/search?q=Iran+oorlog+2026+laatste+nieuws\nL2: # Search Results\nL3: \nL4: \\\\* 【0†Hoe is het dagelijks leven in Iran nu? ‘Het staakt-het-vuren maakt\nL5: me wanhopig’ - NRC†www.nrc.nl】\nL6: \\\\* 【1†'VS stuurt duizenden extra militairen naar Midden-Oosten'†nos.nl】\nL7: \\\\* 【2†Hoe verloopt de Amerikaanse zeeblokkade, en is er ruimte voor verdere\nL8: onderhandelingen met Iran? - NRC†www.nrc.nl】\nL9: \\\\* 【3†Trump wil snel af van de oorlog in Iran, maar Teheran heeft met de\nL10: Straat van Hormuz en het nucleaire programma twee sterke troefkaarten in handen -\nL11: NRC†www.nrc.nl】\nL12: \\\\* 【4†Iran wijst voorstel staakt-het-vuren af, eist verlichting sancties -\nL13: NRC†www.nrc.nl】\nL14: \\\\* 【5†Blokkade van Chinese schepen en berichten over wapensteun aan Iran\nL15: werpen schaduw op top Xi-Trump - NRC†www.nrc.nl】\nL16: \\\\* 【6†Iran en VS zoeken door naar vermist bemanningslid F-15 in Iran,\nL17: beloning uitgeloofd†www.rtl.nl】\nL18: \\\\* 【7†Extra nieuwsuitzending 8 april 2026 over staakt-het-vuren Iran en\nL19: VS†www.youtube.com】\nL20: \\\\* 【8†VRT NWS Nieuws \\| Betrouwbaar Nieuws uit België \u0026 de\nL21: Wereld†nws.vrt.be】\nL22: \\\\* 【9†Iran-oorlog duwt inflatie omhoog en kan leiden tot wereldwijde\nL23: recessie, waarschuwt IMF†www.rtl.nl】"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1b04fr9b7bb614dbg0dx","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 3, \"id\": 0}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1b1gfrabmht9mcp650m5","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 3, \"id\": 0}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL:\nL2: https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2026/04/15/onder-iraniers-is-de-angst-voor-knallen-afgenomen-maar-wekt-het-staakt-het-vuren-ook-zorgen-a4925029\nL3: Hoe is het dagelijks leven in Iran nu? ‘Het staakt-het-vuren maakt me\nL4: wanhopig’ - NRC\nL5: \nL6: Ga direct naar inhoud\nL7: \nL8: 【0†Terug naar de krant】Lijst\nL9: \nL10: 【1†Terug naar de krant】\nL11: \nL12: Het straatbeeld in Iran komt langzaam weer tot leven, sinds vorige week woensdag\nL13: het staakt-het-vuren met de Verenigde Staten inging. In Teheran zijn de kraampjes\nL14: terug, de straten druk. Voor het eerst in veertig dagen reed een vertaalster (40)\nL15: uit de hoofdstad afgelopen weekend met haar ouders een rondje door de wijk. Ze\nL16: wilden de militaire gebouwen zien die waren geraakt. „Ze zijn volledig met de\nL17: grond gelijk gemaakt”, vertelt ze aan NRC.\nL18: \nL19: Begin vorige week kwam al het werkende leven in Iran weer op gang. Kantoren zijn\nL20: open, kinderen volgen online lessen. Niet vanwege de wapenstilstand — maar\nL21: omdat de twee weken nationale vakantie rond Nowruz, het Iraanse nieuwjaar,\nL22: voorbij waren.\nL23: \nL24: Zo ook voor de receptioniste van een sportcomplex (50) uit Teheran. Tijdens de\nL25: oorlog was zij met haar familie gevlucht naar een dorp bij Isfahan. Op maandag\nL26: belde haar baas: ze moest terugkomen. Het werd ook saai in het dorpje, vertelde\nL27: ze aan haar nicht in Nederland, met wie NRC contact heeft.\nL28: \nL29: Toch is niet alles zoals het was. De Basij (de paramilitaire vrijwilligersmilitie\nL30: van het regime) is nog steeds nadrukkelijk aanwezig. „Die klootzakken rijden\nL31: nog steeds een paar keer per dag met enorme luidsprekers op pick-uptrucks door de\nL32: buurt”, zegt de vertaalster. „Zelfs om twaalf uur ’s nachts. Ik word er gek\nL33: van.”\nL34: \nL35: ## Prijs van gebak en koffie verdubbeld\nL36: \nL37: De inflatie is verder opgelopen. De prijs van gebak en koffie is verdubbeld ten\nL38: opzichte van een maand geleden, merkte de vertaalster vorige week bij de bakker.\nL39: \nL40: Hoewel universiteiten en farmaceutische gebouwen zijn geraakt, bleef de medische\nL41: zorg voor burgers tijdens de oorlog grotendeels intact. Een lerares Engels (40)\nL42: uit Teheran haalde vorige week chemotherapiepillen op bij de apotheek voor haar\nL43: vader. Er waren geen tekorten, en de medicijnen werden nog steeds vergoed via de\nL44: zorgverzekering, vertelt ze via haar zus in Nederland.\nL45: \nL46: Maar niet alles functioneerde. De moeder van een vriendin van de lerares brak\nL47: voor het begin van de oorlog haar heup en is sindsdien immobiel. De\nL48: fysiotherapeut is niet meer langs geweest. Via haar vriendin in Nederland vroeg\nL49: ze om met behulp van AI fysiotherapie-oefeningen op te zoeken — want zelf heeft\nL50: ze door het beperkte internet geen toegang tot zulke programma’s.\nL51: \nL52: Een vrouw (die niet in het stuk voorkomt) zit in een café in het noorden van\nL53: Teheran, afgelopen zondag.\nL54: \nL55: foto Vahid Salemi/AP Zoom in\nL56: \nL57: Vrede met de Islamitische Republiek betekent dat de veiligheid van Iraniërs die\nL58: achterblijven verdwijnt\nL59: \nL60: Het staakt-het-vuren roept bij de Iraniërs met wie NRC contact heeft vooral\nL61: bezorgdheid op. Een tandarts-chirurg (44) uit Teheran kijkt er met gemengde\nL62: gevoelens naar. De angst voor harde knallen is afgenomen — maar het\nL63: vooruitzicht van een akkoord verontrust haar. „Vrede met de Islamitische\nL64: Republiek betekent dat de veiligheid van Iraniërs die achterblijven\nL65: verdwijnt.”\nL66: \nL67: 【2†Lees ook Bij Iraniërs maakt de euforie plaats voor onzekerheid. ‘Zonder\nL68: rugdekking is protesteren zelfmoord’】\nL69: \nL70: Ook de vertaalster volgt de onderhandelingen met groeiende zorg. Zaterdag zag ze\nL71: op satelliet-tv voorbijkomen — van een niet nader genoemde Iraanse bron — dat\nL72: de VS 【3†akkoord†www.reuters.com】zouden zijn gegaan met het vrijgeven van\nL73: zes miljard dollar aan bevroren Iraanse tegoeden in Qatar, in ruil voor vrije\nL74: doorgang door de Straat van Hormuz. Washington ontkende dit. „Ik ben bang dat\nL75: onze belangen worden wegonderhandeld. Het voelt alsof we door de VS zijn\nL76: verraden”, zegt ze.\nL77: \nL78: Een promovenda internationaal recht (40) die vlakbij de Straat van Hormuz woont,\nL79: schrijft: „Het staakt-het-vuren maakt me wanhopig. We voelen ons gijzelaars van\nL80: de Islamitische Republiek.” Hoeveel Iraniërs er zo over denken, is niet vast\nL81: te stellen.\nL82: \nL83: ## Graffiti tegen het akkoord\nL84: \nL85: Vorige week woensdagavond werd het staakt-het-vuren groots gevierd in Teheran. Al\nL86: Jazeera deelde 【4†beelden†www.aljazeera.com】van het\nL87: Enqelab-e-Eslami-plein, waar Iraniërs zwaaiden met vlaggen van het regime en\nL88: foto’s vasthielden van zowel de gedode opperste leider Ali Khamenei als zijn\nL89: opvolger Mojtaba Khamenei. Amerikaanse en Israëlische vlaggen werden verbrand.\nL90: \nL91: Tegelijkertijd is er ook op straat kritiek op het staakt-het-vuren te zien. Op\nL92: het Sa’adat Abad-plein in het noorden van Teheran zag de tandarts-chirurg\nL93: tientallen met spuitbus aangebrachte teksten: ‘Dood aan de hypocrieten’,\nL94: ‘Dood aan de compromissluiters’, ‘Wij onderhandelen niet met de moordenaar\nL95: van de Leider’, ‘Wapenstilstand verboden’. Op zo’n dertig plekken achter\nL96: elkaar, groot op de muren. Om de leuzen te verbergen, staan er controleposten\nL97: voor die met zwarte pick-ups de teksten afdekken, vertelt ze.\nL98: \nL99: Op een 【5†video†x.com】van Iran International, geverifieerd door NRC, is\nL100: te zien hoe loyalisten roepen dat een staakt-het-vuren verraad is aan de Opperste\nL101: Leider. Op 【6†beelden†x.com】uit Isfahan, ook geverifieerd door NRC,\nL102: scanderen regime-loyalisten bij het stadhuis ‘Dood aan de compromissluiters’.\nL103: De tandarts-chirurg vertelt dat op vuilnisbakken bij cinema Azadi en in de wijk\nL104: Yousefabad in het noorden van Teheran de woorden ’trump-bak’ en\nL105: ‘pahlavi-bak‘ gespoten zijn — verwijzend naar Reza Pahlavi, zoon van de\nL106: verjaagde shah en symbool van de monarchistische oppositie.\nL107: \nL108: Zoom in\nL109: \nL110: Zoom in\nL111: \nL112: Het is weer druk in de straten van Teheran, zoals afgelopen maandag bij het\nL113: Enqelab-e-Eslami-plein.\nL114: \nL115: foto’s Vahid Salemi/AP\nL116: \nL117: Over Trumps eerdere dreigementen heeft ze gemengde gevoelens. „Als het erop\nL118: neer was gekomen dat we een paar maanden zonder water, elektriciteit en gas\nL119: zouden zitten, maar de Islamitische Republiek zou verdwijnen — dan was dat het\nL120: voor mij persoonlijk waard geweest.” Tegelijk erkent ze de prijs daarvan.\nL121: „Doordat de infrastructuur niet is aangevallen, zijn patiënten in ziekenhuizen\nL122: en mensen thuis die afhankelijk zijn van gekoelde medicijnen, veiliger. Maar het\nL123: voortbestaan van de Islamitische Republiek betekent extra druk en executies voor\nL124: politieke gevangenen.”\nL125: \nL126: Toch is er ook een klein, onverwacht lichtpuntje. In het zuidenvan Iran begon het\nL127: tijdens de oorlog te regenen — bijzonder in een land dat al jaren 【7†kampt\nL128: met ernstige droogte en watercrisis†www.theguardian.com】. „Als het regent\nL129: gaan de meeste mensen naar binnen”, schrijft de promovenda. „In Iran gaan we\nL130: allemaal de straat op om ernaar te kijken. Het is iets goeds.”\nL131: \nL132: Geef cadeau Deel Mail de redactie\nL133: \nL134: ## Artikel delen\nL135: \nL136: Als cadeau Voor iedereen / Standaard delen Voor NRC-abonnees\nL137: \nL138: Deel dit artikel via sociale media.\nL139: \nL140: - 【8†15 april 2026 om 13:25】Leestijd 4 minuten\nL141: \nL142: - Kopieer link\nL143: \nL144: - E-mail\nL145: \nL146: - WhatsApp\nL147: \nL148: - Bluesky\nL149: \nL150: - Facebook\nL151: \nL152: - LinkedIn\nL153: \nL154: - Mastodon\nL155: \nL156: - Threads\nL157: \nL158: - X\nL159: \nL160: - Reddit\nL161: \nL162: Hoe werkt het delen van artikelen?"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1bq7frgtwqhcj24yxbpw","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"search","arguments":"{\"query\": \"April 2026 Iran war Reuters\", \"topn\": 10, \"source\": \"news\"}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1cnjfrmb4pg4d6zfx5c4","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"search","arguments":"{\"query\": \"April 2026 Iran war Reuters\", \"topn\": 10, \"source\": \"news\"}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL: https://exa.ai/search?q=April+2026+Iran+war+Reuters\nL2: # Search Results\nL3: \nL4: \\\\* 【0†Iran, US receive plan to end hostilities, immediate ceasefire, source\nL5: ...†www.reuters.com】\nL6: \\\\* 【1†Iran says peace talks would be 'unreasonable' following Israeli\nL7: strikes \\| Reuters†www.reuters.com】\nL8: \\\\* 【2†World anxious to open Hormuz Strait while Trump and Iran trade threats\nL9: \\| Reuters†www.reuters.com】\nL10: \\\\* 【3†Trump, Israel pressure Iran ahead of deadline as hunt goes on for\nL11: missing US crew member \\| Reuters†reuters.com】\nL12: \\\\* 【4†Trump agrees to two-week Iran ceasefire, drops threat to destroy\nL13: 'whole civilization' \\| Reuters†www.reuters.com】\nL14: \\\\* 【5†As US and Iran talk truce, Israel digs in for a 'forever war' \\|\nL15: Reuters†www.reuters.com】\nL16: \\\\* 【6†Iran rejects ceasefire as Trump ramps up threats ahead of deadline \\|\nL17: Reuters†today.reuters.com】\nL18: \\\\* 【7†Iran war tests Trump's most enduring political gifts \\|\nL19: Reuters†www.reuters.com】\nL20: \\\\* 【8†US blockade of Iran will be major military endeavor, experts say \\|\nL21: Reuters†reuters.com】\nL22: \\\\* 【9†Reuters \\| Breaking International News \u0026 Views†ara.reuters.com】"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1d9vfrsaeen6wq9wffrj","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 5, \"id\": 0}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1db3frssnp6pa9snbbha","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 5, \"id\": 0}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL:\nL2: https://www.reuters.com/world/china/iran-us-receive-plan-end-hostilities-immediate-ceasefire-source-says-2026-04-06/\nL3: Iran, US receive plan to end hostilities, immediate ceasefire, source says \\|\nL4: Reuters\nL5: \nL6: 【0†Exclusive news, data and analytics for financial market professionalsLearn\nL7: more aboutRefinitiv】\nL8: \nL9: Emergency personnel work at the site of a strike, amid the U.S.-Israeli conflict\nL10: with Iran, in Tehran, Iran, March 12, 2026. Majid Asgaripour/WANA (West Asia News\nL11: Agency) via REUTERS 【1†Purchase Licensing Rights, opens new\nL12: tab†www.reutersconnect.com】\nL13: \nL14: - Summary\nL15: \nL16: - Plan to be agreed on Monday, source says\nL17: \nL18: - Two-stage deal envisaged, ceasefire then final agreement\nL19: \nL20: - Ceasefire could reopen Strait of Hormuz immediately\nL21: \nL22: - Final deal in 15–20 days with nuclear curbs, sanctions relief\nL23: \nL24: - Proposed 'Islamabad Accord' for settlement\nL25: \nL26: April 6 (Reuters) - Iran and the United States have received a plan to end\nL27: hostilities that could come into effect on Monday and ‌reopen the Strait of\nL28: Hormuz, a source aware of the proposals said on Monday.\nL29: \nL30: A framework to end hostilities has been put together by Pakistan and exchanged\nL31: with Iran and the U.S. overnight, the source said, outlining a two-tier approach\nL32: with an immediate ceasefire followed by a comprehensive agreement.\nL33: \nL34: \"All elements need to be agreed today,\" the source said, adding the initial\nL35: understanding would be structured as a memorandum of understanding finalised\nL36: electronically through Pakistan, the sole communication channel in ⁠the talks.\nL37: \nL38: Axios first reported on Sunday that the United States, Iran and regional\nL39: mediators were discussing a potential 45-day ceasefire as part of a two-phase\nL40: deal that could lead to a permanent end to the war, citing U.S., Israeli and\nL41: regional sources.\nL42: \nL43: The source told Reuters Pakistan's army chief, Field Marshal Asim Munir, has been\nL44: in contact \"all night long\" with U.S. Vice President JD Vance, special envoy\nL45: Steve Witkoff and Iranian Foreign Minister Abbas Araqchi.\nL46: \nL47: Under the proposal, a ceasefire would take effect immediately, reopening the\nL48: Strait of Hormuz, with 15–20 days to finalise a broader settlement. The deal,\nL49: tentatively dubbed the \"Islamabad Accord,\" would include a regional framework for\nL50: the strait, with final in-person talks in Islamabad.\nL51: \nL52: There was no immediate response from U.S. and ‌Iranian officials. ⁠Pakistan's\nL53: foreign office spokesperson Tahir Andrabi declined comment.\nL54: \nL55: Iranian officials have previously told Reuters that Tehran was seeking a\nL56: permanent ceasefire with guarantees they will not be attacked again by the U.S.\nL57: and Israel. They have said Iran has received messages from mediators including\nL58: Pakistan, Turkey and Egypt.\nL59: \nL60: The final agreement is expected to include Iranian commitments not to pursue\nL61: nuclear weapons in exchange for sanctions relief and the ⁠release of frozen\nL62: assets, the source said.\nL63: \nL64: Two Pakistani sources said Iran has yet to commit despite intensified civilian\nL65: and military outreach.\nL66: \nL67: \"Iran has not responded yet,\" one source said, adding proposals backed by\nL68: Pakistan, China and the United States for a temporary ceasefire have drawn no\nL69: ⁠commitment so far.\nL70: \nL71: There was no immediate response from Chinese officials to requests for comment.\nL72: \nL73: The latest diplomatic push comes amid escalating hostilities that have raised\nL74: concerns over disruption to shipping through the Strait of Hormuz, a critical\nL75: artery for global oil ⁠supplies.\nL76: \nL77: U.S. President Donald Trump has in recent days publicly pressed for a rapid end\nL78: to the conflict, warning of consequences if a ceasefire is not reached within a\nL79: short timeframe.\nL80: \nL81: The conflict has heightened volatility in energy markets, with traders closely\nL82: watching any developments that could affect flows through the strait.\nL83: \nL84: Reporting by Reuters staff; Editing by Raju Gopalakrishnan\nL85: \nL86: Our Standards: 【2†The Thomson Reuters Trust Principles., opens new\nL87: tab†www.thomsonreuters.com】\nL88: \nL89: ## World\nL90: \nL91: ### US Supreme Court's Sotomayor apologizes to Justice Kavanaugh for 'hurtful'\nL92: comments\nL93: \nL94: 【3†United Statescategory】· April 15, 2026 · 11:39 PM UTC · ago\nL95: \nL96: U.S. Supreme Court Justice Sonia Sotomayor issued an apology on Wednesday for her\nL97: recent criticism leveled at fellow Justice Brett Kavanaugh, an unusual public mea\nL98: culpa that underscores the continuing divisions within the nation's top judicial\nL99: body over its direction and actions in high-profile cases.\nL100: \nL101: 【4†Legalcategory】【5†Trump ally John Eastman is disbarred over bid to\nL102: overturn 2020 election】\nL103: \nL104: 【6†Americascategory】【7†Former Brazil spy chief freed in the US after\nL105: ICE detention, Bolsonaro ally says】\nL106: \nL107: 【3†United Statescategory】【8†Mamdani, Hochul propose tax on New York\nL108: second homes worth more than $5 million】\nL109: \nL110: 【9†Businesscategory】【10†Ukraine official expects US-Ukrainian\nL111: investment fund to approve second project in summer】"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1e6rfs19tvepq15c80a7","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 5, \"id\": 4}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1e83fs1a678gc2fc844w","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 5, \"id\": 4}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL:\nL2: http://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/iran-defiant-eve-trumps-ceasefire-deadline-2026-04-07/\nL3: Trump agrees to two-week Iran ceasefire, drops threat to destroy 'whole\nL4: civilization' \\| Reuters\nL5: \nL6: 【0†Exclusive news, data and analytics for financial market professionalsLearn\nL7: more aboutRefinitiv】\nL8: \nL9: - Summary\nL10: \nL11: - Companies\nL12: \nL13: - Trump says Iran proposal is basis for negotiation\nL14: \nL15: - Iran describes deal as victory over Trump\nL16: \nL17: - Several Gulf countries report Iran missile and drone attacks\nL18: \nL19: - Trump's earlier threat draws international condemnation\nL20: \nL21: WASHINGTON/DUBAI/CAIRO, April 7 (Reuters) - U.S. President Donald Trump agreed to\nL22: a two-week ceasefire with Iran on Tuesday, less than two hours before his\nL23: deadline for Tehran to reopen the Strait of Hormuz or face devastating attacks on\nL24: its civilian infrastructure.\nL25: \nL26: Trump's announcement on social media represented an abrupt turnaround from\nL27: earlier in the day, when he issued an extraordinary warning that \"a whole\nL28: civilization will die tonight\" if ‌his demands were not met.\nL29: \nL30: Pakistan Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif, who helped mediate the ceasefire, said in\nL31: a post on X that he had invited Iranian and U.S. delegations to meet in Islamabad\nL32: on Friday.\nL33: \nL34: Trump said the last-minute deal was subject to Iran's agreement to pause its\nL35: blockade of oil and gas supplies through the strait, which typically handles\nL36: about one-fifth of global oil shipments. Iran's foreign minister, Abbas Araqchi,\nL37: said in a statement that Tehran would stop counter-attacks and provide safe\nL38: passage through the waterway.\nL39: \nL40: \"This will be a double sided CEASEFIRE!\" Trump wrote on his Truth Social\nL41: platform. \"The reason for doing so is that we have already met and exceeded all\nL42: Military objectives, and are very far along with a definitive Agreement\nL43: concerning Longterm PEACE with Iran, and PEACE in the Middle East.\"\nL44: \nL45: Iran's Supreme National Security Council portrayed the deal as a victory over the\nL46: U.S., claiming Trump had accepted Iran's conditions for ending hostilities.\nL47: \nL48: In ⁠response, White House press secretary Karoline Leavitt said: \"This is a\nL49: victory for the United States that President Trump and our incredible military\nL50: made happen.\"\nL51: \nL52: \"The success of our military created maximum leverage, allowing President Trump\nL53: and the team to engage in tough negotiations that have now created an opening for\nL54: a diplomatic solution and long-term peace,\" she said in a post on X.\nL55: \nL56: The war, now in its sixth week, has claimed more than 5,000 lives in nearly a\nL57: dozen countries, including more than 1,600 civilians in Iran, according to\nL58: tallies from government sources and human rights groups.\nL59: \nL60: A source briefed on the talks expressed wariness about the two-week ceasefire\nL61: holding, saying the U.S. side believed Iran might be trying to buy time. It was a\nL62: “trust-building exercise,” the source said.\nL63: \nL64: ## CONDITIONED ON STRAIT'S REOPENING\nL65: \nL66: Two White House officials confirmed that Israel has also agreed to the two-week\nL67: ceasefire and to suspend its bombing campaign on Iran. The agreement includes a\nL68: cessation of Israel's campaign in Lebanon, Sharif said.\nL69: \nL70: It was not immediately clear how soon the ceasefire would take full effect.\nL71: Israeli media reported it would begin once Iran reopened the strait and that\nL72: Israel expected Iranian attacks to continue in the interim.\nL73: \nL74: Item 1 of 10 People wave flags as they gather after a two-week ceasefire in the\nL75: Iran war was announced, in Tehran, Iran. Majid Asgaripour/WANA\nL76: \nL77: \\[1/10\\]People wave flags as they gather after a two-week ceasefire in the Iran\nL78: war was announced, in Tehran, Iran. Majid Asgaripour/WANA 【1†Purchase\nL79: Licensing Rights, opens new tab†www.reutersconnect.com】\nL80: \nL81: Iraq's Islamic Resistance said it would suspend operations in Iraq and across the\nL82: region for two weeks.\nL83: \nL84: More than an hour after Trump's announcement, the Israeli military said it had\nL85: identified missiles launched from Iran, and explosions from intercepted missiles\nL86: could be heard in Tel Aviv. Gulf countries including Kuwait, Bahrain, Saudi\nL87: Arabia and the United ‌Arab Emirates also ⁠issued near-simultaneous alerts\nL88: and activated air defences.\nL89: \nL90: Israeli first responders were providing medical treatment to two 15-year-old\nL91: males who were in mild condition after blast injuries in the southern town of Tel\nL92: Sheva, according to a spokesperson from the MDA ambulance service.\nL93: \nL94: Israeli media said its military was striking back at launch sites in Iran.\nL95: \nL96: Trump, who has issued a series of threats in recent weeks only to back away, said\nL97: progress between the two sides had prompted him to agree to the ceasefire. He\nL98: said Iran had presented a 10-point proposal that was a \"workable basis\" for\nL99: negotiations and that he expected an agreement to be \"finalised and consummated\"\nL100: during the two-week window.\nL101: \nL102: Markets breathed a sigh of relief, with U.S. stock futures rising in the minutes\nL103: following Trump's message. Oil prices fell sharply, with U.S. crude futures\nL104: 【2†touching their lowest price】since March ⁠26.\nL105: \nL106: Global leaders also welcomed the ceasefire with the Australian government saying\nL107: that \"the longer the war goes on, the more significant the impact on the global\nL108: economy will be, and the greater the human cost\".\nL109: \nL110: ## ABRUPT TURNAROUND\nL111: \nL112: Trump's announcement capped a whirlwind day that was dominated by his threat to\nL113: destroy every bridge and power plant in Iran unless Tehran reopened the strait.\nL114: That unnerved world leaders, rattled global financial and energy markets and drew\nL115: widespread condemnation, including criticism from the head of the United Nations\nL116: and Pope Leo.\nL117: \nL118: Some international law experts have said attacking civilian ⁠infrastructure\nL119: indiscriminately could constitute a war crime.\nL120: \nL121: The closure of the strait has sharply increased oil prices, escalating the\nL122: chances of a global economic downturn or even recession. The U.S. Energy\nL123: Information Administration earlier on Tuesday warned that fuel prices\nL124: 【3†could continue to rise for months】even after the strait reopened.\nL125: \nL126: With the U.S. midterm election campaign ramping up, Trump's 【4†approval\nL127: ratings】have hit their lowest level ever, leaving his Republican Party at risk\nL128: of losing its narrow majorities in Congress. Polls show sizable majorities of\nL129: Americans are opposed to ⁠the war and frustrated by the rising cost of\nL130: gasoline.\nL131: \nL132: As the clock ticked down to Trump's 8 p.m. EDT (0000 GMT) deadline, U.S. and\nL133: Israeli 【5†strikes on Iran】had intensified, hitting railway and road\nL134: bridges, an airport and a petrochemical plant. U.S. forces 【6†attacked\nL135: targets on Kharg Island】, home to Iran's main oil export terminal.\nL136: \nL137: Reporting by Reuters bureaus; Writing by Joseph Ax, Simon Lewis and David Dolan;\nL138: Editing by Scott Malone, Cynthia Osterman and Raju Gopalakrishnan\nL139: \nL140: Our Standards: 【7†The Thomson Reuters Trust Principles., opens new\nL141: tab†www.thomsonreuters.com】\nL142: \nL143: ## World\nL144: \nL145: ### Thailand central bank cuts 2026 growth, says no limits to worst-case\nL146: scenarios if war continues\nL147: \nL148: 【8†Asia Pacificcategory】· April 16, 2026 · 12:08 AM UTC · ago\nL149: \nL150: Thailand faces slower growth this year due to the Iran war and there ‌are\nL151: almost \"no limits\" to worst-case economic scenarios if the conflict continues, a\nL152: senior central bank official told Reuters.\nL153: \nL154: 【9†Businesscategory】【10†Pentagon approaches automakers, manufacturers\nL155: to boost weapons production, WSJ reports】\nL156: \nL157: 【11†United Statescategory】【12†US Supreme Court's Sotomayor apologizes\nL158: to Justice Kavanaugh for 'hurtful' comments】\nL159: \nL160: 【13†Legalcategory】【14†Trump ally John Eastman is disbarred over bid to\nL161: overturn 2020 election】\nL162: \nL163: 【15†Americascategory】【16†Former Brazil spy chief freed in the US after\nL164: ICE detention, ally and source say】"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1f8mfsgb8ywghzacf2vz","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"search","arguments":"{\"query\": \"AP april 2026 Iran war ceasefire\", \"topn\": 10, \"source\": \"news\"}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1gb0fsmrn9peb8xrx95b","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"search","arguments":"{\"query\": \"AP april 2026 Iran war ceasefire\", \"topn\": 10, \"source\": \"news\"}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL: https://exa.ai/search?q=AP+april+2026+Iran+war+ceasefire\nL2: # Search Results\nL3: \nL4: \\\\* 【0†Live updates: Pakistan delegation meets Iranian officials hoping for\nL5: ...†apnews.com】\nL6: \\\\* 【1†US-Iran Reach 'In Principle' Deal to Extend Ceasefire:\nL7: AP†www.mediaite.com】\nL8: \\\\* 【2†Pakistani delegation meets with Iranian officials in move to ease\nL9: tensions \\| AP News†apnews.com】\nL10: \\\\* 【3†Trump's ultimatum looms and Iran rejects a ceasefire deal \\| AP\nL11: News†apnews.com】\nL12: \\\\* 【4†US and Iran agree to 2-week ceasefire \\| AP News†uat.apnews.com】\nL13: \\\\* 【5†US military warns it will blockade Iranian ports \\| AP\nL14: News†apnews.com】\nL15: \\\\* 【6†Takeaways after a tentative, 2-week ceasefire reached in Iran war \\|\nL16: AP News†apnews.com】\nL17: \\\\* 【7†Iran says US ceasefire and negotiations are 'unreasonable' - AP\nL18: News†apnews.com】\nL19: \\\\* 【8†US and Iran agree to a two-week ceasefire \\| AP News†apnews.com】\nL20: \\\\* 【9†Iran, U.S. close to agreeing cease-fire extension, officials say \\|\nL21: Fortune†fortune.com】"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1h84fssbr2wd8txgg1wc","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 7, \"id\": 0}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1h98fss8vv8sqd0ghjjh","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 7, \"id\": 0}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL: http://www.reuters.com/differentiator/\nL2: LSEG Partner\nL3: \nL4: ### Reuters and LSEG: an exclusive partnership\nL5: \nL6: LSEG is sole provider of Reuters News to the global financial marketplace.\nL7: \nL8: Financial market professionals get the full power of Reuters News, including\nL9: exclusive access to specialist financial coverage and breaking news alerts,\nL10: optimised for their needs with industry-leading real-time data, analytics and\nL11: workflow tools only via LSEG products.\nL12: \nL13: 【0†Official Data Partner†www.lseg.com】【0†LSEG\nL14: Workspace†www.lseg.com】"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1j9pfswvbny6p2aj9d93","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 7, \"id\": 8}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1jb1fswrkfkth6821dbf","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"open","arguments":"{\"cursor\": 7, \"id\": 8}","approval_request_id":null,"output":"L0: \nL1: URL: http://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/\nL2: Asia News \\| Latest Top Stories \\| Reuters\nL3: \nL4: Skip to main content\nL5: \nL6: 【0†Exclusive news, data and analytics for financial market professionalsLearn\nL7: more aboutRefinitiv】\nL8: \nL9: # Asia Pacific\nL10: \nL11: ago\nL12: \nL13: 【1†North Korea fires 10 ballistic missiles during US-South Korea military\nL14: drills】\nL15: \nL16: North Korea fired more than 10 ballistic missiles into the sea on Saturday, South\nL17: Korea's military said, as the U.S. and South Korean forces conducted military\nL18: drills and U.S. President Donald Trump renewed overtures towards Pyongyang for\nL19: dialogue.\nL20: \nL21: ago\nL22: \nL23: 【2†Thai parliament to open amid scrutiny over election ballots】\nL24: \nL25: ago\nL26: \nL27: 【3†Greek tanker hit by unidentified object near CPC terminal, suffers minor\nL28: damage, operator says】\nL29: \nL30: ago\nL31: \nL32: 【4†Japan, South Korea ready to act against FX volatility, ministers say】\nL33: \nL34: * * *\nL35: \nL36: ago\nL37: \nL38: 【5†Paraguay supports Taiwan. China wants to change that】\nL39: \nL40: ago\nL41: \nL42: 【6†Booming Taiwan can well afford more military spending, president says】\nL43: \nL44: ago\nL45: \nL46: 【7†China urges Afghanistan, Pakistan to resolve tensions via talks, not\nL47: force】\nL48: \nL49: ago\nL50: \nL51: 【8†Pakistani airstrikes cause civilian casualties in Kabul, Taliban and UN\nL52: say】\nL53: \nL54: March 13, 2026\nL55: \nL56: 【9†Exclusive: New US weapons for Taiwan could be approved after Trump's China\nL57: trip】\nL58: \nL59: March 13, 2026\nL60: \nL61: 【10†Taiwan parliament authorises signing of stalled $9 billion US arms\nL62: deals】\nL63: \nL64: ago\nL65: \nL66: 【11†Deceased victim in Virginia shooting served for US in wars, family came\nL67: from Pakistan】\nL68: \nL69: ago\nL70: \nL71: 【12†South Korea PM, Trump discuss possible talks with North Korea's Kim,\nL72: Yonhap says】\nL73: \nL74: * * *\nL75: \nL76: 【13†Chinacategory】· ago\nL77: \nL78: 【14†Panama hopes China's COSCO will resume operations at Balboa port,\nL79: minister says】\nL80: \nL81: Panama's government hopes China's COSCO Shipping will reconsider its decision not\nL82: to use the Balboa port at the entrance of the Panama Canal, the country's\nL83: ‌minister for canal affairs, Jose Ramon Icaza, said on Friday.\nL84: \nL85: 【13†Chinacategory】· ago\nL86: \nL87: 【15†Chinese builder Fantasia unveils sweeping $4.7 billion debt overhaul\nL88: plan】\nL89: \nL90: Embattled Chinese property developer Fantasia on Friday unveiled detailed terms\nL91: of its offshore debt restructuring, including plans to issue new equity,\nL92: convertible bonds and long-dated secured notes.\nL93: \nL94: 【16†Asia Pacificcategory】·March 13, 2026\nL95: \nL96: 【17†ASEAN ministers urge halt to Middle East war as crisis rattles energy and\nL97: trade】\nL98: \nL99: ASEAN foreign and economic ministers on Friday called for an immediate halt to\nL100: the war in the Middle East, and said the effects of surging oil prices and\nL101: ‌disrupted trade are already hitting Southeast Asia's economies.\nL102: \nL103: 【16†Asia Pacificcategory】·March 13, 2026\nL104: \nL105: 【18†Thai family waits for news of missing relative on ship attacked in\nL106: Straits of Hormuz】\nL107: \nL108: Thousands of miles from the Middle East in Thailand's rural northeast, Sommai\nL109: Butdee waits for news of her nephew, one of three crew members missing from the\nL110: Thai-flagged vessel after it was struck with ‌two projectiles earlier this week\nL111: as it travelled through the Strait of Hormuz.\nL112: \nL113: 【16†Asia Pacificcategory】· ago\nL114: \nL115: 【19†Iran plane leaves India with sailors, bodies as Indian ships win Hormuz\nL116: reprieve】\nL117: \nL118: A chartered plane arranged by Iran departed southern India late on Friday\nL119: carrying some sailors from a naval vessel that had docked in the country, as well\nL120: as the bodies of crew members killed in a U.S. attack off Sri Lanka, two sources\nL121: told Reuters.\nL122: \nL123: March 13, 2026\nL124: \nL125: 【20†Veon's core profit rises on digital services as it prepares Starlink\nL126: deployment in Bangladesh】\nL127: \nL128: Digital services operator Veon on Friday reported core profit that was up around\nL129: 19% for ‌its full year, driven by higher demand for digital services as it\nL130: looks to expand its Starlink partnership to Bangladesh next.\nL131: \nL132: 【13†Chinacategory】·March 13, 2026\nL133: \nL134: 【21†'Dream holidays' in disarray, trips diverted as travellers count cost of\nL135: Iran war】\nL136: \nL137: In the remote Western Australian town of Dardanup, accountant Natasha Earle and\nL138: her family are feeling the financial pain of the U.S.-Israeli war with Iran.\nL139: \nL140: 【16†Asia Pacificcategory】·March 13, 2026\nL141: \nL142: 【22†D8 summit in Indonesia delayed due to Middle East war, Indonesian foreign\nL143: ministry says】\nL144: \nL145: A summit of eight major Muslim developing countries, including Iran, that ‌was\nL146: to be held in Jakarta next month has been delayed due to the war in the Middle\nL147: East, an official with Indonesia's foreign ⁠ministry said on Friday.\nL148: \nL149: Loading...\nL150: \nL151: Load more articles"},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1kctft48zxz4rywyd58z","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"search","arguments":"{\"query\": \"April 2026 Iran war BBC\", \"topn\": 10, \"source\": \"news\"}","approval_request_id":null,"output":""},{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcpc_01kpag1mbjft8tmpe9qfnxevxb","status":"completed","server_label":"browser","name":"search","arguments":"{\"query\": \"April 2026 Iran war BBC\", \"topn\": 10, \"source\": \"news\"}","a